page.title: 09Birds in Blean Woods
page.content: This rural area, mainly covered by woodland is rich in bird life. One area, Church Wood, constitutes a National Nature Reserve started in l952. Other interested bodies involved include the Nature Conservancy Council and the R.S.P.B. Some of the land is privately owned. The usual woodland birds can be sighted in the area as well as greater and lesser woodpeckers which inhabit the high canopy areas and the spotted flycatcher which is seen along the open rides. The coppiced areas being rich in insect life are populated by the nightingale, blackcap,garden warbler,whitethroat,chiffchaff and willow warbler. The nightingale's song is often heard as well as the raucous call of the jay.
